SYPHILIS - UK: (SCOTLAND) YOUNG HETEROSEXUALS
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 4 Dec 2013
Source: Evening Telegraph [edited]
http://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/news/local/dundee-s-young-urged-to-take-care-as-syphilis-rates-rise-1.161166


Young people in Tayside have been hit with an outbreak of syphilis. NHS [National Health Service] Tayside has seen a surge in cases of the sexually transmitted infection among heterosexual people aged 15 to 25.

The number of cases currently stands at about 20 -- compared to a usual 3 or 4 -- and those affected pass on the disease to partners in unprotected sex about 50 percent of the time, leading to fears the problem could escalate. The health board has launched an investigation into potential sources of the outbreak, as well as increasing clinic hours for testing. And young people have been urged to get themselves tested in a bid to stop the spread of the disease.

Dr Graham Leslie, a consultant at NHS Tayside's Sexual and Reproductive Health Centre, said: "We have seen an increase in cases of syphilis, and a large proportion of the increase has been in a young heterosexual population, which is unusual. Usually in Tayside we might expect a handful, and this year [2013] we have had 3 or 4 times what we would normally. Over summer we saw a small number of cases that seemed slightly unusual. From autumn onwards, we have suddenly seen more and we are trying to deal with that now. We have seen it across Tayside and from a public health point of view the longer we take to pick up people who might be infected, the more who are affected. Whenever we see an increased number of cases we want to know where they came from and what we could be doing, so we look closely at the cases -- that is ongoing at the moment. We haven't pinpointed where it came in and we may not be able to."

If left untreated, syphilis can cause permanent damage to the brain, the nervous system, and also the heart. Symptoms, which include ulcers, disappear but the infection stays. The longer someone goes untreated the worse the syphilis can become. A simple blood test is all that is needed to diagnose it, while treatment is usually a course of antibiotics.

Dr Leslie said: "We have increased clinical capacity at the sexual health clinic and given easier access to testing. Information has gone out to other health professionals, such as GPs."

Young people are also being targeted for advice at The Corner Health, Information and Peer-led Services for Young People at Shore Terrace in Dundee. Fiona McGrath, who is a health services link leader at the centre, said: "We want to let as many people know so that they can continue to take care of their sexual health. The Corner is a really good 1st point of contact."

If you'd like to know more, visit http://www.cool2talk.org or http://www.sexualhealthtayside.org, or the Need Tay Know app. For information or testing, people can also visit The Corner 6 afternoons a week or the Linc clinic at Ninewells on Mondays and Thursdays between 4pm-6pm.

