Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The news release above reports a large increase in the number of cases of syphilis (50 cases) reported so far this year (2013), compared to the usual number reported annually (3 to 4 cases) in Tayside region, Scotland. Although not specified in the news release, presumably the cases are contagious forms of syphilis (primary, secondary, and early latent syphilis). With a population of about 400 000, the incidence rate for syphilis in 2013 in Tayside is 12.5 per 100 000, in contrast to the incidence rate of 5.8 per 100 000 population in 2012 for Scotland as a whole (http://www.hps.scot.nhs.uk/ewr/redirect.aspx?id=55318) and 5.6 per 100 000 population for England in 2011 (http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=20224). The Tayside cases are said to be occurring among heterosexual people aged 15-25 years of age. Some of this increase could be due to an increase in STI (sexually transmitted infections) screening, but the news release suggests that ongoing high levels of unsafe sexual behavior more likely are behind the rise in syphilis seen among these young people.

We are told these cases are occurring "across Tayside", but not told if any clusters of cases are occurring in any specific locales. For example, Tayside includes the cities of Perth and Dundee. The city of Dundee, the regional urban center, within 1 hour's drive for 400 000 people, has a significantly greater proportion of 20-24 year olds, being mainly students from across the UK and international locations who are attending the University of Dundee, the University of Abertay, and Dundee College (http://www.thpc.scot.nhs.uk/PDFs/HProtection/Tayside%20Joint%20Health%20Protection%20Plan%20v12%2027.05.10.pdf). We are not told if any of the cases of syphilis are occurring among these university students or are within their social network.

In contrast to the syphilis outbreak in Tayside in 2013 that is occurring among heterosexuals, the Health Protection Agency/Scotland reported that for Scotland as a whole 80 percent of the 205 cases of infectious syphilis in 2012 continue to occur among men who have sex with men (MSM) (http://www.hps.scot.nhs.uk/ewr/article.aspx). Only around 40 cases per year (37 in 2012) are acquired heterosexually.

Similarly, in England syphilis continues to be predominantly seen in MSM, with 75 percent (1955/2622) of the male cases being in this group in 2011. Almost a third (620/1955) of MSM diagnosed with syphilis had previously been diagnosed with HIV infection (Savage EJ, Marsh K, Duffell S, et al: Rapid increase in gonorrhoea and syphilis diagnoses in England in 2011. Euro Surveill. 2012; 17(29): pii=20224. Available at http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=20224).

Tayside had been an administrative region in the eastern central lowlands of Scotland. In 1996, it was divided into the council areas of Perth and Kinross, Angus, and the City of Dundee; however, Tayside continues to have a joint health board. For a map showing the location of Tayside, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tayside. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/8zhj.]
